1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4. Nxd4 a6 5. Bd3 Bc5 6. Nb3 Ba7 7. Qe2 d6 {The
flexible move - retaining the option of Nc6 or Nf6 or Ne7 as per White's
scheme of development.} 8. Nc3 {This move is less flexible than Be3, as now
White has lost the opportunity to play c4 and enter into a Maroczy Bind set-up.
Hence 8. Be3 is a much more flexible option.} (8. Be3 Nc6 9. Nc3 b5 {Merely
transposes...}) 8... Nc6 9. Be3 {White usually exchanges the strong bishop on
a7.} b5 $5 {Black gains space on the queen side with this move. At the same
time, after bishop takes a7, rook takes on a7, the Black rook will have
excellent mobility on the second rank.} (9... Nge7 $5 {Would have kept options
open, waiting for White to reveal his cards.} 10. O-O (10. O-O-O b5 {Would
lead to a nice attacking position for Black.}) 10... e5 {Gives a more
positional character to the game.}) 10. Bxa7 (10. O-O-O {Is a risky move, just
as in the game, as the Black pawns can attack both knights on c3 and b3.} b4
11. Na4 Bd7 {The a4-knight is poorly placed and this constitutes an advantage
for Black.}) 10... Rxa7 11. Qe3 b4 $1 {Pushing the c3 knight away and gaining
more space.} 12. Ne2 (12. Na4 {Was a better square for the knight than e2.} Nf6
13. O-O (13. O-O-O {Is always a risky move in such positions, as Black has
better attacking prospects than White due to his farther advanced queen side
pawns.}) 13... O-O 14. f4 e5 $1 {A very typical idea, fixing the pawns on
light squares.} 15. f5 d5 $1 {Black has an excellent position.}) 12... Nge7 $1
{I particularly like this mode of development. The knight is well placed on
the e7 square - more so than on f6 - because it can go to g6 to defend the
Black king side successfully.} 13. f4 O-O 14. O-O-O $6 {It's illogical that
after Black has played b5-b4, White should 0-0-0! In this way, Black gets a
great attacking position.} (14. O-O {Was a much better choice. But Black can
continue naturally with...} Ra8 15. Rad1 Qc7 16. c4 bxc3 17. Nxc3 Rb8 {Gives
Black good play.}) 14... a5 15. Nbd4 Qb6 $1 {Pinning the knight.} 16. Qg1 Nxd4
17. Qxd4 {White quickly goes to the endgame and tries to limit his losses; but,
as we know, Sicilian endgames often favour Black because of his central
majority and half-open 'c' file.} Qxd4 18. Nxd4 Ba6 19. Nb5 $6 {Black is
better now in the endgame of bishop v knight.} (19. Bxa6 Rxa6 20. f5 e5 21. Nb5
{Was better when White has some pressure, but Black can neutralise it with...}
Rd8 {When the position is sort of equal.}) 19... Bxb5 20. Bxb5 d5 $1 21. exd5
Nxd5 {And Black is ahead here. He has a better pawn structure and his knight
on d5 is extremely strong. Overall, the opening was a huge success for Black.}
