{This is an extremely interesting game between a hugely experienced Indian GM
Thipsay and a talented Indian IM Prathamesh.} 1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 e6 3. d4 cxd4 4.
Nxd4 a6 5. Bd3 Bc5 6. Nb3 Ba7 7. Qe2 Nc6 8. Be3 d6 9. O-O Nge7 10. c4 e5 $1 {
Clamping down on the dark squares.} 11. Nc3 O-O 12. Rad1 {This is a very
logical move, putting the rook on the semi-open file and intending to put
pressure on the backward d6 pawn.} Be6 {A very nice, coherent developing move.}
13. Nd5 {If you ask one question here - what was the drawback to my opponent's
last move - then you will come to the conclusion that the knight no longer
controls the b5 square. Hence we try further to increase control over the dark
squares. But how do we do it? One way of increasing our control is to remove
the opponent's pieces that are controlling the dark squares. In this instance,
the knight on b3 is controlling the d4 and c5 squares, and hence Black
continues a5 with the idea of pushing the b3 knight away.} a5 $1 14. Bxa7 (14.
